Accused of hacking and/or using 3rd party utilities and banned back during the first year of the game, I was unable to find out what they thought I did, what their supposed proof was, or ANYTHING. I was guilty until proven innocent, but in addition denied being able to know anything I'd supposedly done (to either go 'oh, ok, I can see why you'd think that', or discover and plug account hacking from someone else that was 'me' and doing what they'd actually seen, to 'that isn't a 3rd party ANYTHING to do with EQ, you twits'). I could appeal the decision... to their director of customer service, who just told me to drop it and start a new account, and that the evidence was incontrovertable...  but that I couldn't see any of the evidence, or even get vague outlines with any more details than 'you were bad in a way that violates the EULA regarding hacking the client, hacking the game, hacking our servers, or running third party cheat programs'.<br>
<br>
Since I happened to like the game, had a host of friends in game, and was anything but elite (the highest character on my 6 month old account was L21ish or so), I started a new account and hoped whatever had happened before wouldn't happen again. And have been playing since. I KNOW they mistargeted me. I was in the very first rush to ban folks, before Kunark came out. Obviously they weren't REALLY sure of whatever they were up to, or they wouldn't have told me so frankly I could get another account and play. They were banning folks during that round to get them out forever.<br>
I even got to participate in the Kunark beta on my new account, with the same name, address, and credit card info. Hardly what you do with one of the first 20 'examples' of what happens to bad people.<br>
<br>
Annnnnyway, I have every confidence they can screw up. I have every confidence that if they did screw up, there'd be NOTHING an innocent user could do to defend themselves, nor could they ever get an honest accounting of whatever proof the company used as the basis of bannings or whatnot. I've been there already. I'm absolutely against anything that could encourage them to make the same mistakes again, or empower them to be morons and nail people who aren't breaking any rules but might have 'suspicious' processes running and simply be told they're hackers and exploiters out of hand.<br>
<br>
I'm glad you're optimist enough to think they're careful, responsible people who never abuse power, but I'm one of the burned and refuse to give them that much credit with the other examples (see: prior bannings they defended tooth and nail, only to retract a few weeks later. Though this is also proof they're not as utterly arrogant and intractable as they used to be).<br>
